e":"Overleden","1278–Male":"1278–Overleden","1282–Female":"1282–Overleden","1349":"1349","1327":"1327","about 1349":"circa 1349","1323":"1323","1278":"1278","AFT    1371":"na 1371","1331":"1331","about 1323":"circa 1323","1371":"1371","1282":"1282","about 1331":"circa 1331","Llnfhngl Nnt Mln,Llythyfnwg,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Crugeryr,Llnfhngl Nnt Mln,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wales":"Wales"},"en":{"about 1323–AFT    1371":"about 1323–after 1371","1323–1371":"1323–1371","1327–Female":"1327–Deceased","1331–Female":"1331–Deceased","1349–Male":"1349–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1278–Male":"1278–Deceased","1282–Female":"1282–Deceased","1349":"1349","1327":"1327","about 1349":"about 1349","1323":"1323","1278":"1278","AFT    1371":"after 1371","1331":"1331","about 1323":"about 1323","1371":"1371","1282":"1282","about 1331":"about 1331","Llnfhngl Nnt Mln,Llythyfnwg,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Crugeryr,Llnfhngl Nnt Mln,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Einion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Pinning</b> (see   Penning  ) with <i>-ion</i> substituted for <i>-in(g)</i>, perhaps through false association with the word <i>pinion</i> ‘wing, feather’. Compare   Pinyan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Penning","meanings":["English, Dutch, and North German: from early Middle English <i>penning</i>, Low German <i>penning</i>, Middle Dutch <i>penninc</i> ‘penny’ (see   Penny  ), a topographic name (from a field name) or a nickname referring to tax dues of a penny.","South German: from the short form, <i>Panno</i>, of an ancient Germanic personal name derived from a word meaning ‘ban, order, command’.","English: from a Middle English personal name <i>Pening</i>, <i>Pining</i>, presumably representing an unrecorded Old English name, a pet form perhaps of <i>Penda</i> or of names like <i>Pendhere</i> and <i>Pendwulf</i>."]},{"name":"Pinyan","meanings":["English: variant of   Pinion  ."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Philip ap Einion was born about 1323, in Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Einion Sais ap Hywel, was 47 and his mother, Mrs. Einion Sais ap Hywel, was 43. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Mrs. Philip ap Einion. He died after 1371."},"et":{"about 1323–AFT    1371":"umbes 1323–pärast 1371","1323–1371":"1323–1371","1327–Female":"1327–Surnud","1331–Female":"1331–Surnud","1349–Male":"1349–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1349":"1349","1327":"1327","about 1349":"umbes 1349","1323":"1323","1278":"1278","AFT    1371":"pärast 1371","1331":"1331","about 1323":"umbes 1323","1371":"1371","1282":"1282","about 1331":"umbes 1331","Llnfhngl Nnt Mln,Llythyfnwg,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Crugeryr,Llnfhngl Nnt Mln,Radnorshire,Wales":"Radnorshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 1323–AFT    1371":"noin 1323–1371 jälkeen","1323–1371":"1323–1371","1327–Female":"1327–Kuollut","1331–Female":"1331–Kuollut","1349–Male":"1349–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1278–Male":"1278–Kuollut","1282–Female":"1282–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1327":"1327","about 1349":"noin 1349","1323":"1323","1278":"1278","AFT    1371":"1371 jälk